column211: What should you do if you have a blood glucose above target (high)?

column296: What is an insulin pump? (Choose all that apply)
column299: An alternate way to deliver insulin instead of through a syringe or pen
column302: A device that delivers both rapid- and long-acting insulins
column305: A device that will check your blood sugar and deliver insulin automatically
column308: A device that delivers insulin continuously through a small catheter that you program  and manage
column311: A device that delivers rapid-acting insulin only
column314: Basal insulin is: (Choose all that apply)
column326: Basal insulin is: (Choose all that apply)
column338: Given to correct high blood glucose levels
column341: Using an insulin pump means you don’t have to check your blood sugar or take any more injections!
column344: The insulin pump will automatically deliver a bolus when needed without you telling it what to do.
column347: What are your goals for starting on an insulin pump?
column350: Starting an insulin pump takes a lot of time and work, and it can be very frustrating at times. How much time do you think is reasonable for things to settle in? Why?

column18: Poor weight gain or poor growth?
column208: Hiding food in his/her/your room or “sneaking” food?
column211: Change in dietary intake (eating significantly more or less than usual)
column214: Avoiding certain food groups ex: dairy, gluten, grains.
column217: Eating/feeding less than usual FOR MORE THAN A WEEK?
column220: Diminished physical activity or sudden increase in physical activity
column223: Hgb A1c increased by 1% or more (example: from 7 to 8%)?
column288: Concern with high blood sugars after eating
column296: Concerns with bowel movements (e.g. too watery or constipated)
column314: Concerns with stomach pains, nausea, vomiting affecting intakes
